{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698243/1937111501/0280.xml":{"full_text":"52\nRedmond's Trick Shots\nIntrigue D. C. Golf Fans\nTurkey Tests\nFeature\nClub Play\nMILLS SHOOTS ACE\nBy CHICK KENNY\nGolfdom\u2019s round-the-world rep\nresentative, Jack Redmond, who\nhas shot his favorite game in the\nbig-game country of darkest Africa\nto the colorful terrain of New\nGuinea and about 1.999 other\ncourses throughout the length and\nbreadth of the universe, staged ex\nhibition matches at Indian Spring\nand Woodmont yesterday to give\nthe clubmen of these institutions\na treat.\nRedmond announced that he\nwould take in the Pinehurst play\nthis week and will depart from\nhere tonight.\nJack told a hot one yesterday\nthat took place several years ago\nin Cleveland, which brings up the\nname of the Forest City\u2019s great\nball player. Tris Speaker.\nIt so happened that Redmond\nwas staging an exhibition of trick\nshots at fashionable Shaker i\nHeights. The committee in charge\nof arrangements strung a row of j\ntoy balloons across a gully and of\nfered prizes to the lucky divoteer\nwho could break one of the bal- I\nloons.\nAll who tried the feat, failed.\nRedmond stepped up and an\nnounced that he could break the\nred one. However, the hard hit\npellet splattered the blue balloon\nthat hung along side the red.\nTris, who was bordering the large\nturnout witnessing the perform-;\nance of Redmond exclaimed\naloud:\n\"Mr. Redmond is color blind. I\nHe hit the ballon he aimed for.\u201d I\nThe crowd thought it was a\ngreat shot (and indeed it was)\nwent off singing the praises of\nRedmond. The \u2019round-the-world\ngolfer accepted one of the prizes!\nAnd now for the happenings\nalong the turkey tourney front:\nLadies carried on for the bird\nof the season at Beaver Dam and\nIndian Spring, while the mascu\nline gender competed for the fowl\nat Argyle.\nMrs. Ora Emge, Beaver Dam\nClub champion, won the net and\ngross honors at her favorite\ncourse by bagging a 96-7\u201489.\nOther winners included Mrs. C. E.\nPurdy and Mrs. Gude with net\n935, while Sara Brissenden, Bessie\nTaylor, Mrs. R. Carl Mitchell and\nMrs. Dlugensky followed close be\nhind for \u201cbirds.\u201d\nAt Indian Spring a field of 24\ncompeted among the ladies for\nThanksgiving dinner. The win\nners were Mrs. Richard Kreuz\nberg, 81; Mary Bernard, 88, and\nMrs. Frank Kennedy, 90.\nW. A. Covert with 80-13\u201467\nbarged through with a turkey at\nArgyle and E. A. Drake with 85-15\n\u20147O came in second.\nTurkey play will continue next I\nSunday with Congressional, Wash\nington, Beaver Dam and Indian\nSpring staging such events to\nclose out the intra-club golf play!\nfor the year.\nThe three-way playoff for the'\nRobert T. Smith president\u2019s cup\nat Congressional was annexed by 1\nH. L. Anderson, who tallied an\n85-15\u201470, to eliminate Claude\nRippy and Gene Pittman. The\nthree had tied for top honors in\nplay last week.\nA hole in one was registered at\nColumbia yesterday, when S. N.\nMills scored such a shot on the\neighth hole. He was playing with\nM. Mackley.\nThe week-end found a flock of I\nthe local professionals departing\nfor Pinehurst, where they will\nplay in 36-holes best ball event\nlisted at the North Carolina re\nsort tomorrow and Wednesday.\nThese include Cliff Spencer, for\nmer Beaver Dam pro; Roland\nMacKenzie, Congressional; Leo\nWalper, Bethesda driving range|\nproprietor; George Diffenbaugh,\nIndian Spring, and Al Treder,\nManor.\nGillie Young, Con gressional\namateur, and Joe Cronin, Boston\nRedsox manager, who plays out\nof Indian Spring, is also on hand\nat Pinehurst.\nCOURTMMES\nAT HINE GYM\nBasketball will get an auspicious 1\nstart tonight at Hine Junior High\nSchool, Seventh and C Streets,\nwhen Bureau of Investigation\nBlues, composed of ex-college stars,\nstack up against Merrick Boys\nClub, with Joe Judge, Washing\nton\u2019s beloved first baseman of\nformer years, tossing up the first\nball at 8 o\u2019clock in the opening\ngame of the Southeast Community\nCenter League. At 9 o\u2019clock the\nTrojans will play Marvin Method\nists.\nThe schedule for the week fol\nlows: Tonight, 8 o\u2019clock, Merricks\nvs. B. of I.; 9, Trojans vs. Mar\nvins. Wednesday night, 7:15,\nClarks Service Station vs. Procure\nment; 8:15, National Savings and\nTrust vs. Trojans; 9:15, B of I.\nvs. Marvins. Friday night, 8,\nProcurement vs. National Savings\nand Trust and at 9 o\u2019clock, Riggs\nNational Bank vs. Merricks.\nTelephone Dletrict 7000\nTime I saw Helen-\nWAS xrT IN rw\u00a3 yA* nq Hate\nHEIZ-MAN! 1- WITH BEEIZ DIWMB2\nJ OH,OEAE.! I'M S?\nST\nSCMEBCOS PLEASE j yPAtT-y\nIh\u00a3 MOCGuE -J t 1 GO To -HE\n\n18--Wfr MWIIB I our\nxv EliC\nI IN-rHEDOOHOUfE IHiWntfl\nSB! h HE\nIfW Wo/MAMZ\n<AE-Toss-\nWHO, as, USUAL HAS\nSgT 'J from'The\npart-/ afiek about the I\n<i /s\u2018. tenth drwk- 'friEm\n1917. K n| Fe.ture.\nPHO CHIBEARS\nCONTINUE ROMP\nCHICAGO, Nov. 15.\u2014The Chi\ncago Bears held a stronger grip\nthan ever on first place in the\nwestern division of the National\nProfessional Football League to\nday.\nDisplaying a powerful all-around\noffense, the Bears downed the\nBrooklyn Dodgers by a 29 to 7\ncount here yesterday before a\nmeager crowd of 7,000.\nWith Bronko Nagurski in the\nvan of the attack, Jack Mander\nregistered 16 of the points, most\nof them on two touchdown passes\nhurled by Bernie Masterson.\nMILWAUKEE, Nov. 15.\u2014T h e\nGreen Bay Packers were panting i\non the heels of the Chicago Bears\nin the western division of the pro\nfootball league today. They buried\nthe Philadelphia Eagles under a\nbarrage of passes and skimmed to\nan easy 37 to 7 victory here yes\nterday before 15,000 customers.\nDon Hutson, former Alabama\nstar caught two of the three touch\ndown passes hurled by Arnold Ker\nber.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 15.\u2014The New\nYork Giants of the National Foot\nball League today were smarting\nunder a 17 to 0 setback by the De\ntroit Lions, the locals\u2019 first defeat\nin two months.\nFlashing blinding speed and\ncrushing power, the Lions bewild\nered the Giants completely.\nThe bruising battle put two New\nYork players in a hospital. Dale\nBurnett suffered a severe concus\nsion that barely missed being a\nfractured skull and Ed Widseth's\nshoulder was injured severely.\nDutch Clark, Ace Gutowsky,\nErnie Caddel and Vernon Huff\nman starred for the winners. The\nattendance was 36,000.\nHORSE SHOW\nCla\u00dfg J\u2014Children's Saddle Ponies (chil\ndren under 12) \u2014Won by Silver, ridden\nby Susan Ladd, owned by Norman\nClark, jr.; second. Good News, ridden\nby Laura Anne Hughes, owned by\nCharles Carrice, Bradley Farms, Md.;\nthird. Brunette, ridden and owned by\nAdele Rogers; fourth. Sherry, ridden by\nJean McGill, owned by Ambrose Preece.\nClass ll\u2014Jumping Class (first divi\nsion) (for riding academy horses only\nover three-foot jumps)\u2014Won by Lady\nBee, ridden by Dorothy Barclay, owned\nby Our Riding School; second. Buddy,\nridden by Lettie Warren and owned by\nRiverside Riding Academy; third, Pride,\nridden by Dave Legum, owned by Rus\nsell\u2019s Riding Academv; fourth, Gray Bird,\nridden by Barbara Gableman, owned by\nRiding and Hunt Club.\nClass Hl\u2014Junior Horsemanship Class\n(children under 16)\u2014Won by Gay Melody,\nridden and owned by Elaine McDowell;\nI second. Launcelot. ridden by Laura Anne\nHughes, owned by Dawson Stables; third.\nSilva, ridden by Susan Ladd, owned by\nNorman Clark, jr.; fourth. Gray Bird,\nridden by Barbara Gableman, owned by\nDawson Stables.\nClass IV (jumping class, second divi\nsion, jumps 3\u00bbzi feet) \u2014Won by Wishing\nWell, owned and ridden by Mrs. Am\nbrose Preece: second. Gal Melody, ridden\nand owned by Elaine McDowell; third,\nBlue, ridden by Miss Margaret Evane,\nowned by Argyle Riding School; fourth.\nJeremiah, ridden by Eddie Talbot, owned\nby Mrs. Gladys Heberman.\nClass V (Bridle Path Hacks; Riding\nAcademy horses only)\u2014Won by Wally,\nridden by Miss Jan Brandes, owned by\nNorman Clark, jr.; second, Diana, rid\nden by Miss Farley, owned by Potomac\nRiding School; third, Sister, ridden by\nMrs. R. williams, owned by Potomac\nI Riding School; fourth, Babs, ridden by\nEddie Talbot, owned by Russell Riding\nSchool.\nClass VI (jumping class, third division;\njumps 4 feet) \u2014Won by Midnight, ridden\nI by Mrs. Elizabeth Martin Shoemaker,\nowned by Norman Clark, jr; second, Red\nBird, ridden by Mrs. Leona McKinnon,\nowned by Our Riding School; third. Pop\nover, ridden by Mr. J. B. McWilliams,\nowned by Elias Marks; fourth. Jeremiah,\nridden by Eddie Talbot, owned by Mrs.\nGladys Haberman.\nClass VII (bride path hacks; ridden by\nl private owners)\u2014Won by Lady Jack,\nowned and ridden by Miss Cheerie Mc-\nKee; second. Modern Melody, owned and\nI ridden by Mrs. N. H. McDowell; third.\nGolden Glow, owned and ridden by Ed\ndie Talbot, fourth, Dolly Sile, owned and\nridden by Thomas O\u2019Dononue.\nClass VIII (open jumping class; jumps\nnot to exceed 4 feet)\u2014Won by Modern\nMelody, ridden by Gardner Hallman,\nowned by Mrs. N. H. McDowell; second.\nLady Jack, ridden by Gardner Hallman,\nowned by Miss Chee ie McKee; third.\nPatches, ridden by John West, owned by\nJack Parker; fourth. Easy Money, ridden\nby Mrs. John Burna, owned by Anne\nTitus. (Winner decided by flip of the\ncoin).\nHOCKEY SCORES\nRed Wings.,,,,, 1 Mont. Canadian*., 1\nBoston 1 Rangers 1\nNat\u2019l Football\nLeague\nWESTERN DIVISION\nWon Lost Tie TP OP I\nChicago Bears 6 11 131 65\nGreen Bay Packers 7 2 0 214 98\nDetroit 6 3 0 164 S 5 I\nChicago Cards 5 3 1 100 107\nCleveland ISO 61 176\nEASTERN DIVISION\nWon Lost Tie TP OP\nNew York 5 2 1 91 47\nWASHINGTON ~5 2 0 116 93 i\nPittsburgh 4 6 0 122 122*\nBrooklyn 2 7 0 46 161\nPhiladelphia 2 S 1 86 177\nS. E. Merchants\nDown Hessick Co.\nThe Southeast Merchants con\ntinue their winning streak and\nchalked up a 7-0 victory at the ex\npense of the Hessick Coal Com\npany. The Merchants were held\nscoreless for three quarters, and\nit was not until the fading mo\nments of the last quarter that the\nSoutheast Club scored. Taking\nball in midfield they started a\ndrive which resulted in a touch-i\ndown. Cassidy going over from 1\nthe five-yard mark. Cassidy also I\nconverted the extra point.\nCrossword Puzzle\ni 2\" 3 w 5 i a\nW\n\n17 IS l<?\n2O'~~~ 22\n30 31\n34 35 36 37 3\u00a9 39 HO\n43\n\u00a32. \u2014OA\u2014\nqa 777 \"~T\u2122\n55 56 57 5?\n60\n67 6a 6<? IO 7/\n72\ntF 76\" 77\n70\u2014on fire\n72\u2014 volcano in\nSicily\n73\u2014 molding\n74\u2014 divinely\nsupplied\nfood\n75\u2014 animal hav\ning antlers\n76\u2014 urgent want\n77\u2014 keen\ndispleasure\nVERTICAL\n1\u2014 fluid rock\n2\u2014 expression\nof regret\n3\u2014 controver\nsialist\n4\u2014 sheltered\nside\n5\u2014 follow\nHORIZONTAL\nI\u2014cuplike spoon\n6\u2014worthless\n10\u2014recedes\n14\u2014 strange\n15\u2014 merit\n16\u2014 Iroquois\n17\u2014 decorative\nvessels\n18\u2014 render vain\n20\u2014 means of\nCleopatra\u2019s\nsuicide\n21\u2014 Shoshonean\nIndian\n23\u2014 speak\n24\u2014 espouse\n25\u2014 exhume\n28\u2014paralysis\n30\u2014singing voice\n32\u2014 bleat\n33\u2014 contraction\nof \u201cit is\u201d\n34\u2014 piece of saw\ned timber\n36\u2014making\nopening in\n41\u2014 hastened\n42\u2014 be ill\n44\u2014 mineral\nspring\n45\u2014 low\n46\u2014 cut off\n49\u2014theme of a\ngloss\n51\u2014 piece out\n52\u2014 rage\n54\u2014 marsh grass\n55\u2014 schedule\n58\u2014astral\n60\u2014 .025 acr\u201c\n61\u2014 pose\n63\u2014 wholly\n64\u2014 stitch\n67\u2014aharo\nHerewith is the solution to Satur\nday\u2019s puzzle.\n11 -19\nCourt**. IML k* Kia* Frtum Im.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, MONDAY, NOVEMBER 15, 1937\nThey\u2019ll Do It\nEvery Time\nBy Hatlo\nWASH AN, CORR\u2019S\nWIN GRID GAMES\nBy defeating Georgetown Boys\nClub, 14 to 0, Corr\u2019s Sport Supply\ntightened its grip on first place\nin the National City League's 135-\npound division.\nTaranto Wasman stunned the\nsandlot football public by blank\ning the powerful Regal Clothes,\n7 to 0, in the National City\nLeague\u2019s 160-pound section.\nThe Taranto boys scored late in\nthe final quarter when Vermillion\npassed 15 yards to Daly over the\nend zone. W. Pell converted.\nArmand Carlo\u2019s 95-yard run for\na touchdown from the opening\nkickoff enabled Northeast Boys\nClub to defeat Southwest A. C.,\n6 to 0.\nPlaza A. C. defeated Trinity,\n2 to 0, in a well-played game.\nColumbia Heights Eagles\ndropped Takoma Indians for the\ncount of 13 to 0 on the Takoma\nField.\n6\u2014 assignable 1\n7\u2014 river in 1\nSwitzerland 1\n8\u2014 overcome\ncompletely\n9\u2014 projecting\npart of Sat-\nurn\u2019s rings\n10\u2014 at all times\n(poetic)\n11\u2014 noisy\nquarrel\n12\u2014 lacerates\nwith the\nteeth\n13\u2014 abounding\nin plant\novules\n19\u2014prefigura\ntive\nMARKET TRADE\nLIGHT; ISSUES\nGAIN SLIGHTLY\nI\nRises Reflect Change\nIn Business Outlook\nBy LESLIE GOULD\nNEW YORK. Nov. 15 (1.N.5.).\nThe stock market registered fur\nther improvement in light trading\ntoday with steels, coppers, utilities\nI and building shares the early\nleaders.\nBethlehem was up 2 points, and\nU. S. Steel and Youngstown half\nas much, before realizing pared\nthe gains.\nCOPPERS UP\nGains in the copper section at\none time ran to a point in Ameri\ncan Smelting, Kennecott and An\naconda. The firmer price situation\nover the past few days, coupled\nwith gossip of a possible increase\nin domestic quotations soon, stimu\nlated buying in the group.\nCertain-teed preferred spurted\nmore than 3 points and the com\nmon almost a point in the build\ning division, while U. S. Gypsum\nand Johns-Manville each ad\ni vanced a point. The gains were\nreduced later in the forenoon,\nhowever.\nPOWER GAINS\nThe power group, still reflect\ning the changed administration\nattitude toward the industry,\nshowed gains up to a point in\nNorth American and Public\nj Service of New Jersey.\nFarm implement shares and\nI amusements were inclined to lag\nj through the forenoon. Intema\ntional Harvester was off more\nthan a point. Warner Bros, and\nParamount slipped fractionally.\nOils, rubbers, mail orders and\naviations generally' were moder\nately above previous closing levels.\nCommodities were lower. Wheat\nlost a cent. Cotton was off nearly\n30 cents a bale. Other samples\nfollowed suit. Bonds gave an im\nproved performance.\nThe Weather\nDistrict of Columbia\u2014Fair and\ncolder tonight; Tuesday cloudy\nand colder followed by rain,\nbeginning Tuesday afternoon or\nnight; lowest temperature tonight\nabout 38 degrees; gentle to mod\nerate northwest, shifting to north\nand northeast winds.\nMaryland\u2014Generally fair and\ncolder, except light rain or snow\nflurries in extreme west portion to\nnight; Tuesday cloudy and colder,\nfollowed by rain in east and snow\nor rain in west portion, beginning\nTuesday afternoon or night.\nViginia\u2014Generally fair, colder\nin east and central portions to\nnight; Tuesday cloudy and colder,\nrain Tuesday afternoon or night.\nDEPARTURES\nAccumulated excess of tempera\nture since January 1, 1937. 514.\nExcess of temperature since\nNovember 1, 1937, 48.\nAccumulated excess of precipita\ntion since January 1, 1937, 15.14.\nExcess or deficiency of precipita\ntion since November 1. 1937, 1.91.\nTEMPERATURES\nRa In-\nHieh Low fall\nAsheville, N. C 60 38\nAtlanta. Ga 66 38\nAtlantic City. N. J.. 66 44\nBoston. Mass 5$ 46\nChicago, 11l 40 34 02\nCheyenne. Wyo 5 4 28\nDenver. Colo 58 40\nTies Moines. lowa 38 32\nDetroit. Mich 42 34 0.08\nEl Paso. Tex 74 4 8\nLos Angeles. Cal. 66 56\nMiami. F\u00bba 72 56\nNew York. N. Y 62 46\nOmaha. Neb 40 30\nPittsburgh. Pa 50 43 0 04\nPortland, Me 52 4 2 0.30\nortland. Ore 54 48 0.16\nSan Antonio. Tex,.... 78 66\nSan Francisco, Cal. 62 54 0 06\nSanta Fe. N. M. 56 30\n\nBIDS AND PROPOSALS\nCOMMISSIONERS. D. C.. Washington. No\nvember 10. 1937,\u2014Sealed proposals will\nbe received at Room 509. District Build\ning. until 2:00 p. m November 17. 1937,\nand then publicly opened, for laying 18-\ninch watermain in Pennsylvania Avenue\nbetween Texas Avenue and 33d Place, and\n8-inch watermain in 33d Place between\nPennsylvania Avenue and Carpenter Street,\nand in Carpenter Street, between 33d Place\nand Highwood Drive. S E Apply to\nChief Clerk. Engineer Department. 427 Dis\ntrict Building, for proposals, specifications\nand drawings.\n22\u2014flap\n26\u2014 and not\n27\u2014 coal distil,\nlate\n29\u2014 oleaceous\ntree\n30\u2014 shelter\n31\u2014 permission\nto use\n33\u2014spigot\n35\u2014having least\nlight\n37\u2014 exacted aa\nfine\n38\u2014 dipping\n39\u2014 mining town\nof Alaska\n40\u2014 spur\n43\u2014frost\n47\u2014 food fish\n48\u2014 deep hole\n50\u2014period of\ntime\n53\u2014wing of\nhouse\n55\u2014 bound with\nnarrow band\n56\u2014 acute and\nrugged crest\nof mountain\n57\u2014 sesame\n58\u2014 degree of\nprogression\n59\u2014 animal allied\nto camels\n62\u2014commonest\nmetallie\nelement\n65\u2014 sea bird\n66\u2014 last under\nuse\n68\u2014 pinna or\nauricle\n69\u2014 born\n71\u2014winnow\nPeople Have Wondered\nat such\nFulfillment of Service\nAt Prices So Low\nTHAT IS WHAT MADE CHAMBERS\nONE OF THE LARGEST UNDER-\nTAKERS IN THE WORLD\nFulfillment of service means all the facilities\nthat make It possible for CHAMBERS to tum\nout a complete funeral at much lower cost.\nCompare three funeral homes. 40 assistants, -mu\u00dfrar 1~7\n15 parlors, 7 chapels, 25 cars, hearses and W. W. CHAMBERS\nambulances with the equipment elsewhere %a acLA\navailable. In case of death call CHAMBERS.\nComplete Funerals from $75 up\nChamber}\nMain Office\n14th and Chapin Sts. N.W.\nPhone Columbia 043$\nsl\u00df\u00b0Eteventb beautiful half couch casket\nPhone ATlantie \u00ab700 provided in a complete funeral\nSuharbS\u00df Hem. th at includes cars SIAF\nblwmV'm*. and hearses, all for JqQ\nFbon. Greenwood 1221 only\u2014\nWe Now Have a Complete Flower Department\nWASHINGTON PRODUCE\n(Prices paid shippers\u2014Net F. O. B.\nWashington)\nBy the U. 8. Bureau of Agricultural\nEconomics\nWashington, D. C., Monday. Nov. IK.\nEgg s\u2014 Market about steady and un\nchanged. Government graded and dated\neggs; Whites, U. S. extras, large, 39%\ncents; U. S. extras, mediums, 29 cents;\nU. S. standards, large. 36 cents; U. 8.\nstandards, mediums. 26 cents. Nearby\nungraded eggs: Current receipts. 29 to\n30 cents; whites, 34 to 35 cents, varying\npremium paid on fancy lots, particu\nlarly larger sizes.\nLive Poultry\u2014 Market unchanged. Re\nceipts nf turkeys light this morning\nand undertone generally steady to firm.\nFowl; Colored, heavy, IS to 21 cents;\nNo. 2\u2019s, 13 tn 14 cents; leghorns, 14 to\n16 cents; roosters, 12 to 13 cents.\nChickens: Rocks and Crosses, all sizes,\n25 cents; mixed colors, 20 to 21 cents.\nTurkeys: Hens, 10 to 12 lbs.. 22 to 23\ncents; toms, 14 tn 16 lbs., 20 to 21 cents;\nNo. 2\u2019s and old turkeys, 17 cents.\nGuineas. 2 lbs. and over, 50 cents each;\nunder 2 lbs.. 40 cents each.\nL. C. L. Express Receipts at Washing\nton. D. C., Monday, November, 15, 1937\nFlorida\u2014 97 lugs avocados; 45 lugs\nlimes; 22 bu. boxes limes; 84 bu. baskets\nsquash; 36 bu. baskets okra: 36 bu. boxes\neggplant; 27 bu. baskets parsley; 23 30-\nIb. lugs tomatoes; 50 bu. baskets string\nbeans.\nToday's Most\nActive Stocks\nAm. Wat. Wks. 16% 15% 15%\nAnaconda 32% 32 32\u2019%\nBeth. Steel 56% 55% se\u2019/a\nChrysler Corp 70% 69% 69%\nColum. G& El 11 10% 10%\nCom\u2019wlth &So 2% 2% 2%\nEl Power Lt.. 15 14% 14%\nGen Elec 43% 42% 43%\nGen Motors 40% 40% 40%\nNat Gypsum 9% B'/a 9\nN Y Cent RR.. 21% 20% 20%\nNorth Amer Co 24% 23% 24%\nRepub Steel 20% 19% 20\nUnited Corp 4% 4 4%\nU S Steel 62% 60% 62\nAUCTION SALES\nTHOS. OWEN SON. Auctioneers\n1431 Eje Street, Northwee*\nTRHSTFES\u2019 SALE OF VALUABLE TWO\nSTORY BRICK DWELLING CON-\nNINE BOOMS BATH.\nSTOVE HEAT, ONE CAR GABAGE.\nKNOWN AS PBEMISES 1914\nEIGHTH STREET. NORTHWEST.\nBy virtue of a certain deed of trust duly\nrec